'''Seoul Subway Line 2''' ({{langx|ko|서울 지하철 2호선}}), also known as the '''Circle Line''', is a [[orbital (metro)|circular line]] of the [[Seoul Metropolitan Subway]]. The line running clockwise is called the "inner circle line" and the counter-clockwise line is called the "outer circle line". This is Seoul's most heavily used line, and consists of the main loop ({{convert|48.8|km|mi|abbr=on|sp=us|disp=}}), the Seongsu Branch ({{convert|5.4|km|mi|abbr=on|sp=us|disp=}}) and the Sinjeong Branch ({{convert|6.0|km|mi|abbr=on|sp=us|disp=}}) for a total line length of {{convert|60.2|km|mi|abbr=on|sp=us|disp=}}. The Line 2 loop is the third longest subway loop in the world after Moscow Metro [[Bolshaya Koltsevaya line]] and Beijing Subway [[Line 10, Beijing Subway|Line 10]].{{efn|name=Longest|As of March 2023, Seoul Subway Line 2 is the third longest rapid transit loop line after [[Line 10 (Beijing Subway)|Line 10]] of Beijing Subway and [[Bolshaya Koltsevaya line]] of Moscow Metro.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Moscow Metro launches World's longest metro circle line - Big Circle Line 11|url=https://metrorailtoday.com/news/moscow-metro-launches-worlds-longest-metro-circle-line-big-circle-line-11 |date=1 March 2023|access-date=1 March 2023 |website=Metro Rail}}</ref> When accounting for total distance (+ both branch lines), Seoul Subway Line 2 is the second-longest, only losing out to Bolshaya Koltsevaya line by {{convert|1.5|km|mi|abbr=on|sp=us|disp=}}.}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exploremetro.com/blog/beijing-subway-line-10-if-you-like-it-then-you-should-have-put-a-ring-round-it|title=Beijing Subway Line 10: "If you like it then you should have put a ring round it"|date=December 9, 2012}}</ref> In 2019, Line 2 had an annual ridership of 812 million passengers or 2.2 million passengers per day.<ref>{{Cite web|title=서울시 지하철수송 통계|url=http://data.seoul.go.kr/dataList/273/S/2/datasetView.do#none|access-date=21 May 2021|website=data.seoul.go.kr|language=ko}}</ref>

Headways on the line vary from 2 minutes 18 seconds on peak periods <ref>[http://www.ytn.co.kr/_ln/0103_201011220834048850 [사회&#93;서울 지하철2호선 출근길 배차간격 12초 짧아져]. Ytn.co.kr (2010-11-22). Retrieved on 2013-07-12.</ref> and 5–6 minutes off-peak periods. The line connects the city centre to [[Gangnam (Seoul)|Gangnam]], [[Teheranno|Teheran Valley]] and the [[COEX]]/[[KWTC]] complex.

== History ==
{{More citations needed section|date=July 2024}}[[File:Subway sign Seoul Metro.jpg|thumb|Former [[split-flap display]] passenger information system signs used on Seoul Subway Line 2 from 1980 until replaced with flat-screen TV displays in 2005–10.]]
[[File:지하철 2호선 2단계 개통 기념 지하철표.jpg|thumb|Commemorative ticket issued for the opening of the second phase of Seoul Subway Line 2 on December 23, 1982.]]
[[File:Early 1980s Seoul Subway Map - Flickr - skinnylawyer.jpg|thumb|Fragment of an early-1980s Seoul Subway map, showing the western two-thirds of the Line 2 loop as a green line.]]
In 1972, then-[[Mayor of Seoul]] {{ill|구자춘|lt=Koo Ja-choon|ko}} (1932–1996) changed the existing plans for the Seoul Subway to better enable connectivity around the growing Seoul City and allow for development to take place across the [[Seoul Metropolitan Area]]. Line 2 was built in 1978–84 together with the Seongsu Branch (the second Sinjeong Branch was built 1989–95). [[Dangsan Railway Bridge]] was closed for reconstruction in 1996 and reopened November 22, 1999. The old steel girder bridge was replaced by a {{convert|1.3|km|adj=on}} long concrete bridge between [[Dangsan station|Dangsan]] on the southern side of the river and [[Hapjeong station|Hapjeong]] on the northern bank. During this period, the inner loop only ran to Dangsan Station, and the outer loop only ran to either Hongik University Station or Hapjeong Station. {{efn|At the time, shuttle buses were deployed between Dangsan Station and Hapjeong Station to minimize passenger inconvenience. On November 22, 1999, the Dangsan Bridge reopened, restoring the entire loop line to service, and the lines reverted to alternate operation on the outer and inner loops.}}

[[Yongdu station]] on the Seongsu Branch (between Sindap and Sinseol stations) is the first station in the Seoul Subway system with operating [[platform screen doors]]. As of 2008 platform screen doors are operating at all stations along Line 2. New [[rolling stock]] has also progressively came on line, replacing older vehicles.
