The '''Gyeongui–Jungang Line''' is a [[commuter rail]] service of the [[Seoul Metropolitan Subway]] system, operating on trackage from the [[Gyeongui Line]] (opened on July 1, 2009) and the [[Jungang Line]] (opened on December 16, 2005).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Seon|title=경기도 "동~서 횡단 전철...첫 노선 27일 개통"|url=http://www.1gan.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=25535|access-date=1 December 2014|publisher=Ilgan Gyeonggi|date=1 December 2014|language=ko|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225062303/http://www.1gan.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=25535|archive-date=25 December 2014}}</ref>

Frequent service is provided between [[Munsan station|Munsan]] and [[Yongmun station (Yangpyeong)|Yongmun]] by 8-car trains, with 6 trains weekdays and 5 on weekends running one station east of Yongmun to [[Jipyeong station|Jipyeong]]. However, some services (run by 4-car trains) split for [[Seoul Station]] east of [[Gajwa station|Gajwa]]. Additionally, many trains terminate at various locations on the line such as Ilsan, Neunggok, Daegok, Yongsan, Cheongnyangni, Deokso, and Paldang.

Trains travel along the Gyeongui (Munsan-Seoul Station/Gajwa), Yongsan (Gajwa-Yongsan), Gyeongwon (Yongsan-Hoegi), and Jungang (Hoegi-Jipyeong) lines.

The line runs on the left-hand side of the track, like all other Korail-run Seoul Metropolitan Subway lines.

Travel time is approximately 3 hours all the way and many express services cut the time to 2h 15 min

The color shown on the map is [[Jade (color)|jade]].

== History ==
[[Image:Korail EMU Class 331000.jpg|right|250px|thumb|A Class 331000 train bound for [[Deokso station]] arriving at [[Sangbong station]].]]

2005:
:December 16: The [[Jungang Line]] section is officially opened from [[Yongsan station|Yongsan]] to [[Deokso station|Deokso]] as the '''Yongsan-Deokso Line.'''

2007:
:December 27: The Jungang Line section is extended eastward from Deokso to [[Paldang station|Paldang]]. The Yongsan-Deokso Line is renamed to the '''Jungang Line.'''

2008:
:December 29: The Jungang Line section is extended eastward from Paldang to [[Guksu station|Guksu]].

2009:
:July 1: The [[Gyeongui Line]] section is officially opened from [[Munsan station|Munsan]] to [[Digital Media City station|Digital Media City]] as the '''Gyeongui Line''', with a spur line to [[Seoul Station]].
:December 23: The Jungang Line section is extended eastward from Guksu to [[Yongmun station (Yangpyeong)|Yongmun]]. [[Sinwon station]] is opened as an in-fill station on the Jungang Line section.

2010:
:December 21: [[Sangbong station]] and [[Obin station]] open as in-fill stations on the Jungang Line section.

2012:
:December 15: The Gyeongui Line section's main line is extended eastward from Digital Media City to [[Gongdeok station|Gongdeok]].

2014:
:October 25: [[Gangmae station]] opens as an in-fill station on the Gyeongui Line section.
:December 27: The Gyeongui Line section is extended eastward from Gongdeok to Yongsan, and the present '''Gyeongui-Jungang Line''' is formed after Gyeongui and Jungang lines are merged.

2015:
:October 31: [[Yadang station]] opens as an in-fill station.

2016:
:April 30: [[Hyochang Park station]] opens as an in-fill station.

2017:
:January 21: The line is extended eastward from Yongmun to [[Jipyeong station|Jipyeong]].

2020:
:March 28: A shuttle service began operating between Munsan and [[Imjingang station|Imjingang]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.naver.com/korfan0628430/221866577605|title=Korail KNR|website=[[Naver Blog]]}}</ref>{{Unreliable source|reason=Self-published blog|date=March 2024|certain=yes}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kojects.com/2020/01/05/transport-developments-korea-2020/|title=Transport Developments in Seoul and Korea for 2020|date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>

2021:
:January 5: Express service is modified, with all trains running express on the Gyeongui Line portion of the line now stopping at Yadang and Tanhyeon, and all main line trains running express on the Gyeongui Line portion stopping at Unjeong.
:December 11: Another shuttle service began operating between Imjingang and [[Dorasan station|Dorasan]], finally replacing "Commuter Train" service along the whole Gyeongui Line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/area/capital/919551.html|title=경의선 '문산역~임진강역' 전철 내년 3월 개통|date=December 4, 2019|website=[[The Hankyoreh]]}}</ref>
2022:
:December 17: [[Uncheon station]] opens as an in-fill station between Imjingang and Munsan after being relocated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gukjenews.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=1254501|title=국토부, 경의선 파주 운천역 건립 승인|date=March 10, 2020|website=국제뉴스}}</ref>

===Future Plans===
An in-fill station at Hyang-dong, between Hwajeon and Susaek, is expected to open in 2025.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mygoyang.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=49873 | title=향동지구 입주시작, 향동역 4~5년 뒤 완공 | date=18 February 2019 }}</ref>

== Rapid (Express) trains ==
Korail operates a variety of express "rapid" (급행) trains for [[regional rail|regional]] services on the Gyeongui–Jungang Line. These services include:
*[[Gyeongui Line]] express services via the [[Seoul Station]] branch, operating express between [[Munsan station|Munsan]] and [[Gajwa station|Gajwa]] and then continuing as local trains to Seoul Station.
*[[Gyeongui Line]] express services via the [[Yongsan Line]], operating express between Munsan and Yongsan and then continuing as local trains on the Jungang Line (east of Yongsan).
*[[Jungang Line]] express services, operating express between Yongmun and Yongsan and then continuing as local trains on the Gyeongui Line (west of Yongsan).

== Stations ==
<small>''<span style="color: #ff0000">'''GY'''</span>: Gyeongui Line Express, via the [[Yongsan Line]]''</small><br />
<small>''<span style="color: #ff0000">'''GS'''</span>: Gyeongui Line Express, to Seoul Station via Sinchon station''</small><br />
<small>''<span style="color: #ff0000">'''J'''</span>: Jungang Line Express''</small>

===Current Routes===
*Munsan — Yongmun (most trains)
*Munsan — Seoul Station/Deokso/Paldang/Jipyeong (selected trains)
*Munsan — Imjingang ('''I''' shuttle)
*Imjingang — Dorasan ('''D''' shuttle)
*Munsan — Yongmun (<span style="color: #ff0000">'''GY'''</span> express, Yongsan — Yongmun all stops)
*Munsan — Seoul Station (<span style="color: #ff0000">'''GS'''</span> express)
*Munsan — Yongmun (<span style="color: #ff0000">'''J'''</span> express, Munsan — Ichon all stops)

